WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.700 --> 00:00:05.290
&gt;&gt; Speaker 1: From the Library
of Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:20.560 --> 00:00:21.860
&gt;&gt; Betsy Peterson: Hello everyone.

00:00:21.860 --> 00:00:23.510
Can you hear me?

00:00:23.510 --> 00:00:28.150
Okay. Hi. I'm Betsy
Peterson and I'm the director

00:00:28.150 --> 00:00:31.340
of the American Folklife Center
here at the Library of Congress.

00:00:31.340 --> 00:00:35.640
And on behalf of the Library
and the AFC staff I want

00:00:35.640 --> 00:00:37.750
to welcome you here today.

00:00:37.750 --> 00:00:42.820
This is the latest in our
Benjamin Botkin lecture series,

00:00:42.820 --> 00:00:46.750
and the Benjamin Botkin
lecture series allows the AFC

00:00:46.750 --> 00:00:48.380
to do a number of things.

00:00:48.380 --> 00:00:53.040 position:56%
I mean most importantly to highlight
the work of leading folklorists,

00:00:53.040 --> 00:00:57.650 position:56%
ethnomusicologists, oral historians,
and other cultural specialists,

00:00:57.650 --> 00:01:02.030
enabling them to share their
latest research with all of us.

00:01:02.030 --> 00:01:06.360
But for the center and for
the library it also helps us

00:01:06.360 --> 00:01:08.550
in terms of our acquisitions.

00:01:08.550 --> 00:01:12.970
These lectures are tape
recorded and do become part

00:01:12.970 --> 00:01:18.780
of our collections here at the
library, and will ultimately be

00:01:18.780 --> 00:01:20.730
on the website and be webcasts.

00:01:20.730 --> 00:01:24.900
So with all of that said,
and bringing up webcasts,

00:01:24.900 --> 00:01:29.330
if you have a cell phone on
right now, please turn it off.

00:01:29.330 --> 00:01:31.560
I would appreciate it.

00:01:31.560 --> 00:01:33.510
And today I have the honor

00:01:33.510 --> 00:01:37.580
of introducing the distinguished
folklorist and longtime friend

00:01:37.580 --> 00:01:40.680
of the American Folklife
Center, Bert Feintuch.

00:01:40.680 --> 00:01:45.130
Doctor Feintuch is a professor of
folklore in English and director

00:01:45.130 --> 00:01:49.370
of the Center for the Humanities
at the University of New Hampshire.

00:01:49.370 --> 00:01:53.110
Under his leadership the
center at the University

00:01:53.110 --> 00:01:56.090
of New Hampshire has built
a significant endowment,

00:01:56.090 --> 00:02:00.600 position:56%
developed numerous interdisciplinary
programs, supported hundreds

00:02:00.600 --> 00:02:02.910
of faculty research projects,

00:02:02.910 --> 00:02:06.760
become home to several
notable undergraduate programs,

00:02:06.760 --> 00:02:10.820
and has developed a study
abroad program in Ghana.

00:02:10.820 --> 00:02:12.120
And that's not all.

00:02:12.120 --> 00:02:13.570
He does more.

00:02:13.570 --> 00:02:18.320
As a folklorist, Bert has
published on traditional music,

00:02:18.320 --> 00:02:21.710
cultural conservation,
and other numerous topics

00:02:21.710 --> 00:02:24.630
in traditional and
vernacular culture.

00:02:24.630 --> 00:02:29.480
From 1990 to 1995 he
served as the editor of the

00:02:29.480 --> 00:02:31.580
"Journal of American Folklore."

00:02:31.580 --> 00:02:34.690
He has also done extensive
ethnographic research

00:02:34.690 --> 00:02:37.500
in traditional music
cultures in Great Britain,

00:02:37.500 --> 00:02:39.380
the United States, and Canada.

00:02:39.380 --> 00:02:42.770
And he is particularly
well known for his research

00:02:42.770 --> 00:02:46.250
on the traditional music and
culture of Northumberland

00:02:46.250 --> 00:02:51.230
and Cape Breton Island, and he is
also a musician in his own right.

00:02:51.230 --> 00:02:54.660
With David Waters he published
the critically acclaimed

00:02:54.660 --> 00:02:56.650
"Encyclopedia of New England."

00:02:56.650 --> 00:03:01.930
And his 2010 book "In The
Blood, Cape Breton Conversations

00:03:01.930 --> 00:03:06.200
on Culture" won an independent
publisher book award.

00:03:06.200 --> 00:03:10.220
His latest book, "Talking New
Orleans Music" was recently

00:03:10.220 --> 00:03:15.020
published by the university
press of Mississippi.

00:03:15.020 --> 00:03:17.250
And there continues to be more.

00:03:17.250 --> 00:03:21.480
Bert has also produced
recordings for Smithsonian Folkways

00:03:21.480 --> 00:03:23.320
and for the Rounder label.

00:03:23.320 --> 00:03:27.690 position:56%
He serves on the Library of Congress
prestige's national recording

00:03:27.690 --> 00:03:29.320
preservation board.

00:03:29.320 --> 00:03:33.410
And for five years he represented
the American Folklorist Society

00:03:33.410 --> 00:03:37.060
at the meeting of the World
Intellectual Property Organization.

00:03:37.060 --> 00:03:39.790
He's been awarded numerous
grants and fellowships

00:03:39.790 --> 00:03:43.650
by the National Endowment for the
Humanities, National Endowment

00:03:43.650 --> 00:03:47.550
for the Arts, the American
Council of Learned Societies,

00:03:47.550 --> 00:03:53.060
the US Department of Justice, the
New Hampshire Humanities Council,

00:03:53.060 --> 00:03:56.720
the New Hampshire State
Council on the Arts,

00:03:56.720 --> 00:04:00.390
and other agencies
and organizations.

00:04:00.390 --> 00:04:04.480
Are you tired yet, Bert?

00:04:04.480 --> 00:04:09.810
In addition, in 2012 Bert was
elected as one of the fellows

00:04:09.810 --> 00:04:12.600
of the American Folklore Society.

00:04:12.600 --> 00:04:17.850
Today I'm delighted to introduce
Bert who is going to be talking

00:04:17.850 --> 00:04:20.880
about cultural integrity
and local music,

00:04:20.880 --> 00:04:23.540
Cape Breton fiddle,
New Orleans funk.

00:04:23.540 --> 00:04:28.510
So please give Bert
Feintuch a warm welcome.

00:04:28.510 --> 00:04:32.530
[ Applause ]

00:04:32.530 --> 00:04:33.830
&gt;&gt; Bert Feintuch: Thank you.

00:04:33.830 --> 00:04:37.520
That's -- It's great to see old
friends and colleagues here.

00:04:37.520 --> 00:04:40.710
It feels like a real honor to be
-- have been invited to give a talk

00:04:40.710 --> 00:04:42.010
at the Library of Congress.

00:04:42.010 --> 00:04:44.170 position:56%
I want to thank Nancy Gross [assumed
spelling] in particular for the --

00:04:44.170 --> 00:04:47.530
all the work that she put
in to the logistics of this.

00:04:47.530 --> 00:04:50.150
And again such a treat to see some

00:04:50.150 --> 00:04:54.010
of my fairly old friends
and colleagues too.

00:04:54.010 --> 00:04:56.610
I also want to recognize
my significant other,

00:04:56.610 --> 00:04:58.110
Jeanie Thomas [assumed
spelling], is here,

00:04:58.110 --> 00:05:02.870
a folklorist from the University
of -- from Utah State University.

00:05:02.870 --> 00:05:06.480
And Jeanie kind of rode shotgun
on a lot of the fieldwork

00:05:06.480 --> 00:05:11.110
that is the basis of what I'll
be talking about this afternoon.

00:05:11.110 --> 00:05:14.290
Speaking of field work, let's see.

00:05:14.290 --> 00:05:16.700
Get myself organized here.

00:05:16.700 --> 00:05:21.280
Speaking of field work, for me
probably the thing I like best

00:05:21.280 --> 00:05:24.680
about being a folklorist
is doing field work.

00:05:24.680 --> 00:05:27.450
It's something I love to do.

00:05:27.450 --> 00:05:31.340
I -- Sitting down with a
musician who I admire or,

00:05:31.340 --> 00:05:34.820
to use a New Orleans term, a
culture bearer who I admire,

00:05:34.820 --> 00:05:39.040
with a recording device on the
table between us, is often sort of,

00:05:39.040 --> 00:05:42.810
you know, one of the
highlights of my life.

00:05:42.810 --> 00:05:48.550
And I also come to realize
after being in this field

00:05:48.550 --> 00:05:52.550
for a very long time that, you
know, academic ideas come and go,

00:05:52.550 --> 00:05:56.760
but the materials that we create
doing field work become part

00:05:56.760 --> 00:06:00.400
of an enduring record and
that seems to me to be,

00:06:00.400 --> 00:06:03.630
if I think about any significance
to what I've been doing

00:06:03.630 --> 00:06:07.220
over the years -- That seems
to be what is most significant.

00:06:07.220 --> 00:06:12.260 position:56%
I've done field work all over the
place, it feels like for decades now

00:06:12.260 --> 00:06:16.190 position:56%
in the United Kingdom, in the
United States, and various locations

00:06:16.190 --> 00:06:18.820
on sort of both ends of
Canada and British Columbia

00:06:18.820 --> 00:06:21.810
and Canadian Maritimes too.

00:06:21.810 --> 00:06:26.220 position:56%
And, as I think back, I realize
that what seems to draw me to places

00:06:26.220 --> 00:06:30.680
where I do ethnographic field work
is that these are often places

00:06:30.680 --> 00:06:32.520
that I've come to think

00:06:32.520 --> 00:06:35.930
of as musical hotspots
or creative hotspots.

00:06:35.930 --> 00:06:39.920
There's something that sets these
places off from other places

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:45.920
when it comes to the vitality
and significance of local music.

00:06:45.920 --> 00:06:49.440
They're often places where
music is deeply rooted,

00:06:49.440 --> 00:06:53.440
where it's very much valued,
where it's well integrated

00:06:53.440 --> 00:06:55.580
and connected to identity.

00:06:55.580 --> 00:06:59.700
You know, for roots music
people, if I say Chicago,

00:06:59.700 --> 00:07:01.420
you -- Something comes to mind.

00:07:01.420 --> 00:07:03.240
You think blues.

00:07:03.240 --> 00:07:05.250
Chicago is a great example of that.

00:07:05.250 --> 00:07:07.100
If I say Omaha, maybe less so.

00:07:07.100 --> 00:07:10.920
For instance, not that there's
not, I'm sure, terrific local music

00:07:10.920 --> 00:07:14.420
in Omaha, but it never kind
of rose to the kind of level

00:07:14.420 --> 00:07:17.150
of public awareness and
appreciation that some

00:07:17.150 --> 00:07:21.220
of these other sort
of hotspots have done.

00:07:21.220 --> 00:07:26.260 position:56%
The more I spend time in these
sorts of places talking to musicians

00:07:26.260 --> 00:07:28.720
and culture bearers and citizens,

00:07:28.720 --> 00:07:31.650
the more I see some
commonalities despite all the kinds

00:07:31.650 --> 00:07:33.620
of obvious differences too.

00:07:33.620 --> 00:07:38.540
And so today I want to talk
about two musical hotspots,

00:07:38.540 --> 00:07:42.800
seemingly very different places
where I've done field work.

00:07:42.800 --> 00:07:48.180
I talk about Cape Breton in Nova
Scotia and about New Orleans.

00:07:48.180 --> 00:07:49.480
Do you know Cape Breton at all?

00:07:49.480 --> 00:07:50.930
Some of you probably do.

00:07:50.930 --> 00:07:52.440
Yeah. Good.

00:07:52.440 --> 00:07:56.040
Good. So I'm realizing, in fact,

00:07:56.040 --> 00:07:59.060
that this year is not
only the 50th anniversary

00:07:59.060 --> 00:08:02.910
of "Sergeant Pepper's
Lonely Hearts Club," man,

00:08:02.910 --> 00:08:04.750
but I think it's the
20th anniversary

00:08:04.750 --> 00:08:06.120
of my first trip to Cape Breton.

00:08:06.120 --> 00:08:10.180
And I can't tell you how
many times I've been there.

00:08:10.180 --> 00:08:14.460
I'm not hearing about that
as much on NPR, though.

00:08:14.460 --> 00:08:20.310
So Cape Breton has been a sort
of long running obsession for me.

00:08:20.310 --> 00:08:24.630
New Orleans a little bit
less so in that the work

00:08:24.630 --> 00:08:28.880
in New Orleans I've tried to focus
more on control and not allow it

00:08:28.880 --> 00:08:34.450
to become that kind of obsession
that Cape Breton has formed for me.

00:08:34.450 --> 00:08:36.510
Both have led to various
publications

00:08:36.510 --> 00:08:38.360
and some sound recordings
and things like that,

00:08:38.360 --> 00:08:40.370
and I'm showing you these book
covers really because I want

00:08:40.370 --> 00:08:43.650
to acknowledge the fact that these
have been collaborative projects

00:08:43.650 --> 00:08:46.420
that I've had the privilege
of working

00:08:46.420 --> 00:08:48.490
with a really fine
photographer and an old friend,

00:08:48.490 --> 00:08:50.370
a guy named Gary Sampson
[assumed spelling] who I know

00:08:50.370 --> 00:08:53.990
from New Hampshire who in fact
was just named artist laureate

00:08:53.990 --> 00:08:57.000
for the state of New Hampshire.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:01.590
So, you know, what drew me to
these very different places?

00:09:01.590 --> 00:09:04.390
You know one is just sort
of sheer self indulgence

00:09:04.390 --> 00:09:08.350
in that there are places that
produce music that I love.

00:09:08.350 --> 00:09:12.270
And they're also places where
I've come to understand, you know,

00:09:12.270 --> 00:09:14.830
people have the kind of
good fortune to be able

00:09:14.830 --> 00:09:16.600
to dance to their own music.

00:09:16.600 --> 00:09:21.900
That is I'd like to say they're
not people who don't know Beyonce

00:09:21.900 --> 00:09:24.820
or whatever, but they're people
too who have the sort of privilege

00:09:24.820 --> 00:09:28.960 position:56%
of having come up in a place where
the local music is still very strong

00:09:28.960 --> 00:09:33.980
and vital and somehow lives
alongside the more industrial more

00:09:33.980 --> 00:09:36.920
popular music that
we all experience.

00:09:36.920 --> 00:09:41.000
These are also places where culture
is in the air, I like to say.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:45.360
That there's often a kind of
public conversation about the value

00:09:45.360 --> 00:09:49.870
and significance of culture
or music and its importance

00:09:49.870 --> 00:09:52.530
to the integrity of local life.

00:09:52.530 --> 00:09:55.990
They're places where
people see music, in fact,

00:09:55.990 --> 00:10:00.870
as integral to a good life, where
it stands for a kind of wholeness

00:10:00.870 --> 00:10:04.070
of integrity in local culture.

00:10:04.070 --> 00:10:07.970
So I hope you note that I'm using
these words integral, integrity,

00:10:07.970 --> 00:10:10.310
and so forth, and this is in
part because I want to try

00:10:10.310 --> 00:10:13.290
to develop an idea that
I've been thinking about,

00:10:13.290 --> 00:10:19.040
this idea of cultural integrity
which I work my way toward.

00:10:19.040 --> 00:10:23.030
But first let me talk to
you about Cape Breton.

00:10:23.030 --> 00:10:25.050
Cape Breton is an island
that is part

00:10:25.050 --> 00:10:27.500
of the Canadian province
of Nova Scotia.

00:10:27.500 --> 00:10:29.930
I feel very accomplished in
PowerPoint that I managed to get

00:10:29.930 --> 00:10:34.260
that arrow on this
screen, by the way.

00:10:34.260 --> 00:10:36.070
That was a first for me.

00:10:36.070 --> 00:10:38.310
So it's an island just
about 4,000 square miles.

00:10:38.310 --> 00:10:39.720
That makes it like times --

00:10:39.720 --> 00:10:41.760
almost three times the
size of Rhode Island,

00:10:41.760 --> 00:10:46.220
but 130,000 people there
now and steadily declining.

00:10:46.220 --> 00:10:52.570
The population has been declining
precipitously for decades now.

00:10:52.570 --> 00:10:59.070
It was settled -- The largest group
of people to move to that island,

00:10:59.070 --> 00:11:01.760
the largest sort of contingent
of settlers, were people who came

00:11:01.760 --> 00:11:05.100
from the highlands and
western islands of Scotland.

00:11:05.100 --> 00:11:09.360
They came in the late
1700s through about 1847

00:11:09.360 --> 00:11:15.000
or so when the population
movement ended.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:18.500
They got there and they found a
thin scattering of native people

00:11:18.500 --> 00:11:23.560
or first nations people, as
Canadians say, a thin scattering

00:11:23.560 --> 00:11:26.820
of francophones, French
speaking people who were there

00:11:26.820 --> 00:11:31.350
as a consequence of early
French fishing and exploration.

00:11:31.350 --> 00:11:34.160
And some Anglophones too
who were also there in part

00:11:34.160 --> 00:11:38.350
because of the fishing and
in part because loyalists

00:11:38.350 --> 00:11:42.600
from New England tended
to move north and east

00:11:42.600 --> 00:11:46.220
when things weren't
going so well for them.

00:11:46.220 --> 00:11:50.270
And it is a musical hotbed.

00:11:50.270 --> 00:11:54.910
It is centered on the fiddle.

00:11:54.910 --> 00:11:56.860
The fiddle is often accompanied

00:11:56.860 --> 00:11:59.340
by [inaudible] a very
distinctive style.

00:11:59.340 --> 00:12:01.930
And these days too we're
seeing a resurgence of interest

00:12:01.930 --> 00:12:04.930
in the highland pipes too which
is a very different scene.

00:12:04.930 --> 00:12:07.710
If you think of highland pipes you
think of people in kilts marching

00:12:07.710 --> 00:12:10.430
in formation or in a
kind of military way.

00:12:10.430 --> 00:12:14.070
At Cape Breton the pipers sit down
and they play them for dancing

00:12:14.070 --> 00:12:19.960
and it's a much different way of
approaching the instrument too.

00:12:19.960 --> 00:12:22.620
And it's dance music.

00:12:22.620 --> 00:12:25.980
People dance to the
music in local halls.

00:12:25.980 --> 00:12:29.880
When I first came to
Cape Breton 20 years ago,

00:12:29.880 --> 00:12:32.130
especially on the western
side of the island

00:12:32.130 --> 00:12:35.490
which is Inverness
County it seemed to me

00:12:35.490 --> 00:12:37.070 position:56%
that the music was just every place.

00:12:37.070 --> 00:12:43.240
I felt really astonished at
how present and vital it was.

00:12:43.240 --> 00:12:46.300
There were dances just about
every night of the week.

00:12:46.300 --> 00:12:50.400
This was summer when things
are more active there.

00:12:50.400 --> 00:12:54.430
You could sit in a fast food
place and the radio would be on

00:12:54.430 --> 00:12:55.730
and you'd heard a country song

00:12:55.730 --> 00:12:57.030
and then you'd hear a
local fiddle player.

00:12:57.030 --> 00:12:59.680
I mean hear another country song.

00:12:59.680 --> 00:13:00.980
Something like that.

00:13:00.980 --> 00:13:03.250
You'd -- There were
festivals every weekend.

00:13:03.250 --> 00:13:06.160
If you got lucky you got invited
to a house party where people sat

00:13:06.160 --> 00:13:09.230
and took turns playing for
the assembled crew of people.

00:13:09.230 --> 00:13:14.150 position:56%
The local newspaper which on that
side of the island is a weekly paper

00:13:14.150 --> 00:13:18.440
in the summer devoted more pages to
coverage of music than to sports.

00:13:18.440 --> 00:13:22.990
It was really quite astonishing.

00:13:22.990 --> 00:13:25.450
I think I like this crowd.

00:13:25.450 --> 00:13:32.400 position:56%
At one time I went to an event early
on where people bought tickets.

00:13:32.400 --> 00:13:34.200
They actually paid for tickets

00:13:34.200 --> 00:13:38.830
to hear an ethnomusicologist
interview two older musicians,

00:13:38.830 --> 00:13:41.880
and that's when I realized
I'd found paradise.

00:13:41.880 --> 00:13:46.980
I want to show you a kind
of blurry video from one

00:13:46.980 --> 00:13:48.390
of those community dances.

00:13:48.390 --> 00:13:51.600
Going to try to link to YouTube.

00:13:51.600 --> 00:13:56.660
I'll tell you that this is in the
community of [inaudible] Village

00:13:56.660 --> 00:14:01.490
and this is a kind of
typical venue for a dance.

00:14:01.490 --> 00:14:06.130
It is -- There are two kinds of
community dances in Cape Breton,

00:14:06.130 --> 00:14:08.220
and that has to do
with the liquor laws.

00:14:08.220 --> 00:14:11.040
In Nova Scotia you have to
be 19 to be able to drink.

00:14:11.040 --> 00:14:15.200
The dances where they sell
beer or other alcohol rather

00:14:15.200 --> 00:14:19.640
than just share it in the parking
lot are called adult dances.

00:14:19.640 --> 00:14:22.890
And then there are also family
dances where no alcohol is sold.

00:14:22.890 --> 00:14:27.080
This is an adult dance, but I
think you'll notice that even

00:14:27.080 --> 00:14:29.250
in this case it's sort

00:14:29.250 --> 00:14:33.070
of a multigenerational
sort of experience as well.

00:14:33.070 --> 00:14:34.420
In fact, you're just
going to see the dancing.

00:14:34.420 --> 00:14:35.850
You're not going to
see the musician.

00:14:35.850 --> 00:14:38.740
I don't have time to
find a good clip,

00:14:38.740 --> 00:14:40.980
but I should tell you
about the musician.

00:14:40.980 --> 00:14:45.070
The fiddle player is named Rodney
McDonald who's a step dancer

00:14:45.070 --> 00:14:48.730
and a fiddle player and a member
of a musical dynasty, a family --

00:14:48.730 --> 00:14:51.590
His first recording, which
he did with a cousin,

00:14:51.590 --> 00:14:57.680
they did a family tribute on 44
other musicians in the family tree.

00:14:57.680 --> 00:15:03.340 position:56%
And at 34 Rodney was elected premier
of the province of Nova Scotia

00:15:03.340 --> 00:15:06.090
which is equivalent to governor
so they had a fiddle player

00:15:06.090 --> 00:15:07.900
and step dancer as governor.

