00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:20.120
That is a fear that the music is
going away, that it's in decline.

00:20:20.120 --> 00:20:25.160
That all of it can be embraced by
this idea of cultural integrity.

00:20:25.160 --> 00:20:26.570
I like the sound of that.

00:20:26.570 --> 00:20:29.500
You know, I like the sound
of saying cultural integrity.

00:20:29.500 --> 00:20:33.350
And for a while I thought maybe
I'd made it up, but it's not so.

00:20:33.350 --> 00:20:38.350 position:56%
I mean you know Google tells me that
I'm not the first, but it also shows

00:20:38.350 --> 00:20:41.280
that nobody has really kind of
written about that term and thought

00:20:41.280 --> 00:20:47.420 position:56%
about it very much, but it's used
sometimes to imply that to be secure

00:20:47.420 --> 00:20:52.150
in one's culture and in one's
community is a good thing.

00:20:52.150 --> 00:20:56.290
My friend, the ethnomusicologist
Jeff Titan, pointed out to me

00:20:56.290 --> 00:20:57.650
when we were talking about this

00:20:57.650 --> 00:21:01.640
that some environmental
scholars use the term integrity.

00:21:01.640 --> 00:21:04.630
And I want to look at
something here with you.

00:21:04.630 --> 00:21:09.090 position:56%
This is from a retired
environmentalist from the University

00:21:09.090 --> 00:21:12.840
of Toronto named Henry
Regier who's written

00:21:12.840 --> 00:21:17.840
about what he calls
ecological integrity.

00:21:17.840 --> 00:21:19.230
I guess I should read it.

00:21:19.230 --> 00:21:22.830
He says, "A living system
exhibits integrity if when subject

00:21:22.830 --> 00:21:26.410
to disturbance it sustains
an organizing self correcting

00:21:26.410 --> 00:21:29.430
capability to recover toward
an end state that's normal

00:21:29.430 --> 00:21:31.300
and good for that system."

00:21:31.300 --> 00:21:35.660
And that really got me thinking.

00:21:36.930 --> 00:21:40.470 position:56%
Culture is of course a living system

00:21:40.470 --> 00:21:44.340
in which components
interact with each other.

00:21:44.340 --> 00:21:47.530
And it seems to me that one way
of thinking about this is thanks

00:21:47.530 --> 00:21:51.510
to Regier that culture integrity
involves a kind of resilience

00:21:51.510 --> 00:21:58.220 position:56%
and an ability to sustain what local
people think of as normal and good.

00:21:58.220 --> 00:22:03.410
So I think when I use this term
cultural integrity I'm talking

00:22:03.410 --> 00:22:09.480
about the desire to maintain what a
community values, the local desire

00:22:09.480 --> 00:22:12.500 position:56%
to maintain what a community values.

00:22:12.500 --> 00:22:15.340
I think it's about the sort of
wholeness and interconnectedness

00:22:15.340 --> 00:22:17.020
of life in places like this

00:22:17.020 --> 00:22:21.000
and I don't think every
place is like this.

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:29.200
And also about what I think of as
a sort of ethic of community life,

00:22:29.200 --> 00:22:32.450
the idea, the local idea, that
there's something very good

00:22:32.450 --> 00:22:35.480
and that life is good
in our relationships

00:22:35.480 --> 00:22:38.510
to each other in this community.

00:22:38.510 --> 00:22:40.870 position:56%
Yet another way to think about it is

00:22:40.870 --> 00:22:44.300
when I say cultural integrity
then I'm talking about continuity

00:22:44.300 --> 00:22:47.020
and cohesion and resilience.

00:22:47.020 --> 00:22:51.810
So I want to talk about how
these play out in Cape Breton,

00:22:51.810 --> 00:22:55.280
and then I'll move to talk
