00:49:06.920 --> 00:49:09.600
and family in both of
these places as well.

00:49:09.600 --> 00:49:12.230
You know, as [inaudible]
mentioned, the Cape Breton book

00:49:12.230 --> 00:49:14.520
that we did we called
"In the Blood."

00:49:14.520 --> 00:49:17.310
But I hear people in New Orleans
saying, "Music is in the blood."

00:49:17.310 --> 00:49:19.430
And they're both places
that are characterized

00:49:19.430 --> 00:49:21.940
by these family dynasties.

00:49:21.940 --> 00:49:25.880
In Cape Breton it's
Beatons and McMasters

00:49:25.880 --> 00:49:29.000
and in New Orleans it's
Nevilles and [inaudible]

00:49:29.000 --> 00:49:32.610
and many, many others as well.

00:49:32.610 --> 00:49:37.940
Also in New Orleans the
music is very much part

00:49:37.940 --> 00:49:40.920
of the public realm just
as it is in Cape Breton.

00:49:40.920 --> 00:49:45.360
It's in some ways at the
center of public life.

00:49:45.360 --> 00:49:47.670
In some of these communities too.

00:49:47.670 --> 00:49:50.210
And also, as I mentioned,
there's this ongoing kind

00:49:50.210 --> 00:49:51.690
of public conversation about --

00:49:51.690 --> 00:49:55.580
especially about threats to
those neighborhoods' integrity.

00:49:55.580 --> 00:49:58.110
Often meaning gentrification.

00:49:58.110 --> 00:49:59.830
Formerly it was urban renewal,

00:49:59.830 --> 00:50:01.920
although they've tended
to back down from that.

00:50:01.920 --> 00:50:04.650
And other sorts of
disruptive forces.

00:50:04.650 --> 00:50:07.680
So, as in Cape Breton, New Orleans
is a place where there's a lot

00:50:07.680 --> 00:50:11.190
of kind of cultural
anxiety too, I think.

00:50:11.190 --> 00:50:14.550
And, as in Cape Breton, there's
this development of a kind

00:50:14.550 --> 00:50:17.750
of institutionalized
infrastructure to teach

00:50:17.750 --> 00:50:19.490
and sustain and present the music.

00:50:19.490 --> 00:50:21.940
That is to maintain
cultural integrity.

00:50:21.940 --> 00:50:25.710
I'm thinking New Orleans of,
oh, the Tipitina's Foundation

00:50:25.710 --> 00:50:28.990
and Ellis Marsalis Center
for Music which some

00:50:28.990 --> 00:50:32.390
of these were built
after Hurricane Katrina.

00:50:32.390 --> 00:50:33.960
Some predate them.

00:50:33.960 --> 00:50:37.430
The Marsalis Center which is an
after school center for children --

00:50:37.430 --> 00:50:41.540
They come mostly middle school
and I think high school kids come.

00:50:41.540 --> 00:50:43.990
They have tutors who insist
that they do their homework

00:50:43.990 --> 00:50:45.420
and then they get music lessons.

00:50:45.420 --> 00:50:48.450
I asked the director there,
"What's the instrument that most

00:50:48.450 --> 00:50:50.820
of these young kids want
to play in New Orleans?"

00:50:50.820 --> 00:50:53.400
Thinking that if you ask that
where I live, what would it be?

00:50:53.400 --> 00:50:54.700
Maybe guitar?

00:50:54.700 --> 00:50:56.000
Maybe flute or whatever.

00:50:56.000 --> 00:50:57.910
Trumpet. Trumpet.

00:50:57.910 --> 00:50:59.750
New Orleans.

00:50:59.750 --> 00:51:04.460
There's a New Orleans
[inaudible] alliance, for instance.

00:51:04.460 --> 00:51:11.820 position:56%
And these are all about protecting
or restoring what's normal and good.

00:51:11.820 --> 00:51:13.540
And, as I said, it's
important to realize that some

00:51:13.540 --> 00:51:16.320
of these are the results of
the levees breaking in 2005,

00:51:16.320 --> 00:51:18.110
but some of them predate this.

00:51:18.110 --> 00:51:22.220
These are long running
concerns, long running issues.

00:51:22.220 --> 00:51:30.670
I looked at a 2010 study about
civic engagement and the recovery

00:51:30.670 --> 00:51:37.780
from the hurricane, and they looked
at various kinds of social groups

00:51:37.780 --> 00:51:41.840
in New Orleans and graded them
in terms of civic engagement.

00:51:41.840 --> 00:51:46.290
And some of those constituencies
were high income groups,

00:51:46.290 --> 00:51:50.300
high education groups,
whites, church members.

00:51:50.300 --> 00:51:52.510
The groups that scored highest

00:51:52.510 --> 00:51:59.270
on civic engagement were the
social [inaudible] club members.

00:51:59.270 --> 00:52:02.050
These, as I said, are
benevolent societies

00:52:02.050 --> 00:52:07.130
that were established early in
New Orleans to provide benefits

00:52:07.130 --> 00:52:09.600
that weren't available in African
American communities [inaudible]

00:52:09.600 --> 00:52:14.750
benefits and so forth, but
also played a key role in kind

00:52:14.750 --> 00:52:16.880
of cultural preservation as well.

00:52:16.880 --> 00:52:19.350
They sponsor the parades
that pay the brass bands

00:52:19.350 --> 00:52:22.390
to keep going and things
of that sort.

00:52:22.390 --> 00:52:24.790
So in a sense I see
these organizations

00:52:24.790 --> 00:52:29.430
as having been formed
originally to create

00:52:29.430 --> 00:52:32.280 position:56%
and help sustain cultural
integrity, and that's not surprising

00:52:32.280 --> 00:52:38.870
that they stepped up right
away after the 2005 storm.

00:52:38.870 --> 00:52:41.310
I talked about conversations.

00:52:41.310 --> 00:52:45.650 position:56%
I want to mention that they're
fighting all the time in New Orleans

00:52:45.650 --> 00:52:50.890
about whether music should
be regulated on the streets.

00:52:50.890 --> 00:52:56.570 position:56%
The Mardi Gras Indians have resisted
parade permits historically.

00:52:56.570 --> 00:52:57.870
The city says, "No.

00:52:57.870 --> 00:52:59.170
You need parade permits."

00:52:59.170 --> 00:53:00.790
They are fighting about that.

00:53:00.790 --> 00:53:03.190
And culture is the rationale there.

00:53:03.190 --> 00:53:05.510
It's not expense or whatever.

00:53:05.510 --> 00:53:08.580
Noise ordinances have
become a big issue.

00:53:08.580 --> 00:53:10.700
This is especially in
gentrifying neighborhoods

00:53:10.700 --> 00:53:15.200 position:56%
where you have the kind of familiar
irony of people moving in to an area

00:53:15.200 --> 00:53:17.930
from outside saying they, you
know, they love the culture,

00:53:17.930 --> 00:53:23.510
and then not wanting it
up close very much at all.

00:53:23.510 --> 00:53:27.100
So, to use the terminology
I'm trying to develop --

00:53:27.100 --> 00:53:31.480
So what's normal and good in
some New Orleans neighborhoods is

00:53:31.480 --> 00:53:35.930
under fire typically because
of socioeconomic factors.

00:53:35.930 --> 00:53:38.060 position:56%
The pushback is that these new rules

00:53:38.060 --> 00:53:41.780
and regulations will
damage cultural integrity.

00:53:41.780 --> 00:53:46.060
So I don't mean to imply that
cultural integrity is measurable

00:53:46.060 --> 00:53:51.140
or finite or objective, but in
my field I don't know what is.

00:53:51.140 --> 00:53:53.440
So that doesn't really disturb me.

00:53:53.440 --> 00:53:57.040
We know that from sustainability
studies

00:53:57.040 --> 00:53:59.950
that change is part
of natural systems.

00:53:59.950 --> 00:54:04.940
We also know that environmentalists
believe that there are states

00:54:04.940 --> 00:54:08.430
of being in a natural world that
are more successful which is

00:54:08.430 --> 00:54:13.320
to say more integrated than
other more disruptive states.

00:54:13.320 --> 00:54:17.670
Some environmentalists use
terms such as stewardship

00:54:17.670 --> 00:54:21.140
to describe their work to help
places recover from disruption.

00:54:21.140 --> 00:54:24.910
As I think about Cape Breton,
and as I think about New Orleans,

00:54:24.910 --> 00:54:29.350
and I think about culture being in
the air and about local anxieties

00:54:29.350 --> 00:54:33.280
about culture, I wonder if we
might say that what's at stake

00:54:33.280 --> 00:54:38.330
in these places is a desire to
hold on to cultural integrity.

00:54:38.330 --> 00:54:42.290
And of course I'd like to think
that scholars and institutions

00:54:42.290 --> 00:54:45.350
such as the American Folklife
Center are helping play a role

00:54:45.350 --> 00:54:48.190
in that stewardship, the
stewardship of that integrity.

00:54:48.190 --> 00:54:50.490
Thank you.

